The SEM images obtained of the resultant NPs revealed that IONPs were nearly spherical in shape with size ranging 25–40 nm which were very close to the particle size estimated from mated XRD spectra (Figure 3). Agglomeration can be seen in the SEM images of the subject particles which might be due to electrostatic interaction between layers of NPs surface (Song et al., 2012). However, the obtained results are in close agreement with the previously published results (Kumar, Selvam, & Vadivel, 2012). Remarkably, the spherical shape of the synthesized NPs damage bacterial cell wall which is responsible for maintaining the bacterium's natural shape. The shape of NPs play a basic role in producing pathways for the adsorption of NPs (Lesniak et al., 2013) that eventually cause cell death.
SEM played a key role to explore the size and morphology of the NPs because the biological behavior of the NPs strongly depends on size and shape (Laurent et al., 2008). SEM has proven to be very valuable for the observation of the surface morphology of material, mainly due to improved depth of field and high resolution, which is not available under light microscopy (Butt et al., 2018; Esfandani-Bozchaloyi & Zaman, 2018; Shah, Ahmad, Zafar, Malik, et al., 2018; Shah, Ahmad, Zafar, Razzaq, et al., 2018; Ullah, Zafar, Ahmad, Shah, et al., 2018;
Ullah, Zafar, Ahmad, Dilbar, et al., 2018; Ullah, Zafar, Amhad, Sultana, et al., 2018). In the last few years the SEM has made a massive impact on diverse branches of biological research (Ashfaq et al., 2018; Bahadur et al., 2018; Shah, Celik et al., 2018; Sufyan et al., 2018; Ullah, Papini, et al., 2018; Ullah, Zaman, et al., 2018).
